sec.p:
The experiment began with a learning phase where participants viewed cue‐target sequences and detected the target shapes (see Figure 2). Children were not informed about the assignment of cues and targets or the predictive relationship between them. For example, when  and  were assigned to predict the appearance of  and , the instruction was “please press button V when this fish (pointing to

) appears on the screen; please press button N when this fish (pointing to

) appears on the screen; please do not press any buttons when these two fish (pointing to

and

) appear on the screen.” Each cue or target appeared on screen for 2,000 ms followed by a 500 ms blank interval. Half of the trials contained a free‐viewing task to assess attentional engagement with predictable cues. During these trials, participants viewed two cues appearing simultaneously on screen for 2,000 ms. Eye movements were recorded during the free‐viewing stage. Response accuracy and reaction time were recorded during the target detection task. Each cue object had an equal frequency of appearing on the left and right sides of the screen. Moreover, we ensured an equal possibility of each cue object appearing in each position after each high or low‐TP target to prevent participants from developing any expectation of the display of cue objects in the free‐viewing trials.
